  I also may tank if pet happens to be on a wrong target and ench got his AE stun resisted (though I usually will just hit earthen boots hotkey if the situation might present any danger - in raids for instance).<br>
<br>
 At lower levels (pre 16/20) you certainly don t want your pet to not fight the mob. Your nukes are meaningless compared to the damage dealt by the pet. So you want to fight tough mobs (better exp) and to share your health with your pet, by tanking as much as possible). So root not being needed at all(unless you go hunt in some low lvl dungeon), use water pet for solo as it is a much better tank than the earth, air or fire ones. As an alternative, as soon as your channeling skill is good enough to not get interrupted too easily and as soon as the pet doesn't cost too much mana, chaincasting becomes very interesting expwise (from lvl 12 to 20 roughly). You can solo high yellows and low reds easily even in the tough lvls that way (15 and 19). Now that I think of it, maybe the pet healing lvl 12 spell is better than chaincasting? It didn't exist when I was newb, so I have no idea=).<br>
<br>
 Concerning your fighting method against skellies, well it allows you to be sure to empty all your mana though nukes in the fight. It looks like a good thing to do if u want to solo a mob that you think would be really tough. But nektulos skels happen to be very easy to solo for a lvl 6 mage (they're lvl 4 to 6 right?), so you should try using water pet and just melee a bit, then back off and send a few nukes. That should save your mana, and your pet's life will regen much faster than your mana).<br>
  An even better thing to try is to put your pet on /pet no taunt mode, to pull with a nuke from far range, to press pet attack, then to just run around till the skel dies (skels are a bit slow so you shouldn't need sow, nor your pet. It works very well with mummies wich are even slower). Use some alternate view to check if the mob turns against your pet. When it happens, just send another nuke.<br>
